---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="WAL & Replication: PostgreSQL's Durability & High Availability Engine"
  description="Interactive visualization of PostgreSQL Write-Ahead Logging, streaming replication, logical replication, replication slots, and point-in-time recovery"
  breadcrumbs={[
    { label: "Home", href: "/" },
    { label: "PostgreSQL", href: "/postgresql/" },
    { label: "WAL & Replication", href: "/postgresql/wal-replication/" }
  ]}
>
<div class="viz-container">
  <header class="viz-header">
    <h1>📝 WAL & Replication</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">How PostgreSQL Guarantees Durability and Enables High Availability</p>
  </header>

  <!-- Overview -->
  <section class="overview-section">
    <div class="overview-card">
      <p>
        PostgreSQL uses a <strong>Write-Ahead Log</strong> (WAL) to guarantee that no committed data is ever lost—even
        after a crash. Every change is written to the WAL <em>before</em> it touches the actual data files. This same
        WAL stream powers <strong>streaming replication</strong> (sending changes to standby servers in real-time),
        <strong>logical replication</strong> (decoding changes into logical events), and <strong>point-in-time recovery</strong>
        (restoring to any moment). The WAL is the backbone of PostgreSQL's durability and HA story.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 1: WAL Basics - Step Through -->
  <section class="flow-section">
    <h2>📋 Write-Ahead Log: The Durability Guarantee</h2>
    <p class="section-desc">Every change hits WAL before data files. If PostgreSQL crashes, it replays WAL from the last checkpoint.</p>

    <div class="flow-controls">
      <button id="walStepBtn" class="action-btn primary-btn">▶ Run INSERT Step-Through</button>
      <button id="walNextBtn" class="action-btn step-btn" disabled>⏭ Next Step</button>
      <button id="walResetBtn" class="action-btn reset-btn">🔄 Reset</button>
    </div>

    <div class="wal-pipeline">
      <div class="pipeline-stages">
        <div class="pipeline-stage" id="walStage0">
          <div class="stage-icon">📥</div>
          <div class="stage-label">Client INSERT</div>
          <div class="stage-detail" id="walDetail0">Waiting...</div>
        </div>
        <div class="pipeline-arrow" id="walArrow0">→</div>
        <div class="pipeline-stage" id="walStage1">
          <div class="stage-icon">📝</div>
          <div class="stage-label">WAL Buffer</div>
          <div class="stage-detail" id="walDetail1">Shared memory</div>
        </div>
        <div class="pipeline-arrow" id="walArrow1">→</div>
        <div class="pipeline-stage" id="walStage2">
          <div class="stage-icon">💾</div>
          <div class="stage-label">WAL Disk</div>
          <div class="stage-detail" id="walDetail2">pg_wal/</div>
        </div>
        <div class="pipeline-arrow" id="walArrow2">→</div>
        <div class="pipeline-stage" id="walStage3">
          <div class="stage-icon">✅</div>
          <div class="stage-label">Client ACK</div>
          <div class="stage-detail" id="walDetail3">COMMIT ok</div>
        </div>
        <div class="pipeline-arrow" id="walArrow3">→</div>
        <div class="pipeline-stage" id="walStage4">
          <div class="stage-icon">📄</div>
          <div class="stage-label">Data File</div>
          <div class="stage-detail" id="walDetail4">Lazy write</div>
        </div>
        <div class="pipeline-arrow" id="walArrow4">→</div>
        <div class="pipeline-stage" id="walStage5">
          <div class="stage-icon">🏁</div>
          <div class="stage-label">Checkpoint</div>
          <div class="stage-detail" id="walDetail5">Sync all</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="wal-explanation" id="walExplanation">
      <p>Click "Run INSERT Step-Through" to see how a single INSERT flows through WAL to disk.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="wal-segments">
      <div class="wal-seg-title">pg_wal/ directory — 16MB WAL segments</div>
      <div class="wal-seg-track" id="walSegTrack">
        <div class="wal-seg filled" id="walSeg0">
          <span>000000010000000000000001</span>
          <div class="seg-fill" style="width: 72%;"></div>
        </div>
        <div class="wal-seg" id="walSeg1">
          <span>000000010000000000000002</span>
          <div class="seg-fill" style="width: 0%;"></div>
        </div>
        <div class="wal-seg" id="walSeg2">
          <span>000000010000000000000003</span>
          <div class="seg-fill" style="width: 0%;"></div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="wal-lsn">
        Current LSN: <strong id="walLsnValue">0/1480000</strong>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Explanation: Why WAL? -->
  <section class="explain-section">
    <div class="explain-card highlight-card">
      <h3>💡 Why Write-Ahead Logging?</h3>
      <p>
        Random writes to data files are slow—pages are scattered across disk. Sequential writes to the
        WAL are <strong>fast</strong>. By writing changes sequentially to WAL first, PostgreSQL can
        acknowledge commits quickly, then lazily flush data pages in the background. If a crash occurs,
        the WAL is replayed from the last <em>checkpoint</em> to bring data files up to date. This
        gives you both <strong>performance</strong> (sequential I/O) and <strong>durability</strong>
        (no committed data lost).
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 2: WAL Mechanics - synchronous_commit -->
  <section class="flow-section">
    <h2>⚙️ WAL Mechanics: Durability vs Latency</h2>
    <p class="section-desc">synchronous_commit controls when the server reports success. Lower durability = lower latency.</p>

    <div class="sync-commit-controls">
      <div class="sync-options">
        <button class="sync-option active" data-level="on">on (default)</button>
        <button class="sync-option" data-level="local">local</button>
        <button class="sync-option" data-level="remote_write">remote_write</button>
        <button class="sync-option" data-level="remote_apply">remote_apply</button>
        <button class="sync-option" data-level="off">off</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="sync-viz">
      <div class="sync-timeline">
        <div class="sync-step" id="syncStep0">
          <div class="sync-dot done"></div>
          <div class="sync-label">WAL Buffer Write</div>
        </div>
        <div class="sync-line" id="syncLine0"></div>
        <div class="sync-step" id="syncStep1">
          <div class="sync-dot" id="syncDot1"></div>
          <div class="sync-label">Local WAL Flush</div>
        </div>
        <div class="sync-line" id="syncLine1"></div>
        <div class="sync-step" id="syncStep2">
          <div class="sync-dot" id="syncDot2"></div>
          <div class="sync-label">Remote WAL Write</div>
        </div>
        <div class="sync-line" id="syncLine2"></div>
        <div class="sync-step" id="syncStep3">
          <div class="sync-dot" id="syncDot3"></div>
          <div class="sync-label">Remote WAL Flush</div>
        </div>
        <div class="sync-line" id="syncLine3"></div>
        <div class="sync-step" id="syncStep4">
          <div class="sync-dot" id="syncDot4"></div>
          <div class="sync-label">Remote Apply</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="sync-ack" id="syncAck"></div>
      <div class="sync-info">
        <div class="sync-info-row">
          <span class="sync-info-label">Durability:</span>
          <span class="sync-info-value" id="syncDurability">Full — committed data survives crash</span>
        </div>
        <div class="sync-info-row">
          <span class="sync-info-label">Latency:</span>
          <span class="sync-info-value" id="syncLatency">~1-2ms (local fsync)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="sync-info-row">
          <span class="sync-info-label">Risk:</span>
          <span class="sync-info-value" id="syncRisk">None — standard PostgreSQL guarantee</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Explanation: Full Page Writes -->
  <section class="explain-section">
    <div class="explain-grid">
      <div class="explain-card">
        <h3>📄 Full Page Writes</h3>
        <p>
          After each checkpoint, the <strong>first modification</strong> to any data page writes the
          <em>entire 8KB page</em> into WAL—not just the changed bytes. This protects against
          <strong>torn pages</strong>: if the OS writes only half a page during a crash, PostgreSQL
          can restore the full page from WAL. Increases WAL volume but prevents corruption.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="explain-card">
        <h3>🏁 Checkpoints</h3>
        <p>
          A checkpoint flushes all dirty buffers to data files and writes a checkpoint record to WAL.
          After a crash, recovery only needs to replay WAL <strong>since the last checkpoint</strong>—
          not from the beginning of time. Controlled by <code>checkpoint_timeout</code> (default: 5 min)
          and <code>max_wal_size</code> (default: 1 GB).
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 3: Streaming Replication -->
  <section class="flow-section">
    <h2>🔄 Streaming Replication</h2>
    <p class="section-desc">Primary streams WAL records to standbys in real-time. Hot standbys can serve read queries.</p>

    <div class="flow-controls">
      <button id="replStartBtn" class="action-btn primary-btn">▶ Start Replication</button>
      <button id="replWriteBtn" class="action-btn step-btn" disabled>✏️ Write to Primary</button>
      <button id="replResetBtn" class="action-btn reset-btn">🔄 Reset</button>
    </div>

    <div class="repl-slider-row">
      <label>Network Latency: <strong id="replLatencyValue">50ms</strong></label>
      <input type="range" id="replLatencySlider" min="10" max="2000" value="50" step="10">
    </div>

    <div class="repl-viz">
      <div class="repl-server repl-primary">
        <div class="repl-server-header primary-header">Primary (WAL Sender)</div>
        <div class="repl-server-body">
          <div class="repl-wal-log" id="primaryWalLog">
            <div class="repl-wal-entry">LSN 0/1480000 — CHECKPOINT</div>
          </div>
          <div class="repl-lsn">Write LSN: <strong id="primaryLsn">0/1480000</strong></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="repl-stream">
        <div class="repl-stream-label">WAL Stream</div>
        <div class="repl-stream-track" id="replStreamTrack">
          <div class="repl-stream-packets" id="replPackets"></div>
        </div>
        <div class="repl-lag-bar">
          <div class="repl-lag-label">Replication Lag</div>
          <div class="repl-lag-track">
            <div class="repl-lag-fill" id="replLagFill" style="width: 0%;"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="repl-lag-value" id="replLagValue">0 ms</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="repl-server repl-standby">
        <div class="repl-server-header standby-header">Standby (WAL Receiver)</div>
        <div class="repl-server-body">
          <div class="repl-wal-log" id="standbyWalLog">
            <div class="repl-wal-entry">LSN 0/1480000 — CHECKPOINT</div>
          </div>
          <div class="repl-lsn">Replay LSN: <strong id="standbyLsn">0/1480000</strong></div>
          <div class="repl-badge hot-standby">🟢 Hot Standby — serving reads</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="repl-mode-toggle">
      <span class="repl-mode-label">Replication mode:</span>
      <button class="repl-mode active" data-mode="async">Async</button>
      <button class="repl-mode" data-mode="sync">Sync</button>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 4: Replication Slots -->
  <section class="flow-section">
    <h2>🔒 Replication Slots</h2>
    <p class="section-desc">Slots prevent the primary from recycling WAL segments still needed by a standby.</p>

    <div class="flow-controls">
      <button id="slotWithBtn" class="action-btn primary-btn">▶ With Slot</button>
      <button id="slotWithoutBtn" class="action-btn delete-btn">▶ Without Slot</button>
      <button id="slotNextBtn" class="action-btn step-btn" disabled>⏭ Next Step</button>
      <button id="slotResetBtn" class="action-btn reset-btn">🔄 Reset</button>
    </div>

    <div class="slot-viz">
      <div class="slot-primary">
        <div class="slot-server-label">Primary</div>
        <div class="slot-wal-segments" id="slotSegments">
          <div class="slot-seg active">SEG 1</div>
          <div class="slot-seg active">SEG 2</div>
          <div class="slot-seg active">SEG 3</div>
          <div class="slot-seg">SEG 4</div>
          <div class="slot-seg">SEG 5</div>
        </div>
        <div class="slot-info" id="slotInfo">Standby is connected and caught up.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="slot-standby">
        <div class="slot-server-label">Standby</div>
        <div class="slot-standby-status" id="slotStandbyStatus">
          <span class="slot-status-icon">🟢</span>
          <span class="slot-status-text">Connected — replaying WAL</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="slot-explanation" id="slotExplanation">
      <p>Choose a scenario to see what happens when the standby disconnects.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Explanation: Physical vs Logical Slots -->
  <section class="explain-section">
    <div class="explain-grid">
      <div class="explain-card">
        <h3>📦 Physical Slots</h3>
        <p>
          Retain raw WAL segments—the standby replays the byte-level changes exactly. Used by
          <strong>streaming replication</strong>. Simple, but the standby must have identical schema
          and PostgreSQL major version.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="explain-card">
        <h3>🔀 Logical Slots</h3>
        <p>
          Decode WAL into <strong>logical changes</strong> (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE on specific tables).
          Used by <strong>logical replication</strong>. Allows cross-version replication, selective
          table replication, and data integration with external systems.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 5: Logical Replication -->
  <section class="flow-section">
    <h2>🔀 Logical Replication</h2>
    <p class="section-desc">Publish/Subscribe model — decode WAL into logical changes for selective replication.</p>

    <div class="flow-controls">
      <button id="logicalStartBtn" class="action-btn primary-btn">▶ Start</button>
      <button id="logicalInsertBtn" class="action-btn step-btn" disabled>➕ INSERT order</button>
      <button id="logicalUpdateBtn" class="action-btn step-btn" disabled>✏️ UPDATE order</button>
      <button id="logicalDeleteBtn" class="action-btn delete-btn" disabled>🗑️ DELETE order</button>
      <button id="logicalResetBtn" class="action-btn reset-btn">🔄 Reset</button>
    </div>

    <div class="logical-viz">
      <div class="logical-server logical-pub">
        <div class="logical-server-header pub-header">Publisher</div>
        <div class="logical-server-body">
          <div class="logical-pub-info">
            <code>CREATE PUBLICATION orders_pub FOR TABLE orders;</code>
          </div>
          <div class="logical-table">
            <div class="logical-table-title">orders table</div>
            <div class="logical-table-header">
              <span>id</span><span>product</span><span>qty</span><span>status</span>
            </div>
            <div class="logical-table-body" id="logicalPubBody">
              <div class="logical-row">
                <span>1</span><span>Widget A</span><span>10</span><span>shipped</span>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="logical-stream">
        <div class="logical-stream-label">Logical Decoding</div>
        <div class="logical-stream-track" id="logicalStreamTrack">
          <div class="logical-stream-msg" id="logicalStreamMsg"></div>
        </div>
        <div class="logical-stream-sub">WAL → decoded changes</div>
      </div>

      <div class="logical-server logical-sub">
        <div class="logical-server-header sub-header">Subscriber</div>
        <div class="logical-server-body">
          <div class="logical-pub-info">
            <code>CREATE SUBSCRIPTION orders_sub CONNECTION '...' PUBLICATION orders_pub;</code>
          </div>
          <div class="logical-table">
            <div class="logical-table-title">orders table (replica)</div>
            <div class="logical-table-header">
              <span>id</span><span>product</span><span>qty</span><span>status</span>
            </div>
            <div class="logical-table-body" id="logicalSubBody">
              <div class="logical-row">
                <span>1</span><span>Widget A</span><span>10</span><span>shipped</span>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Physical vs Logical comparison -->
    <div class="compare-grid">
      <div class="compare-card">
        <h3>Physical Replication</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Byte-level WAL shipping</li>
          <li>Entire database cluster</li>
          <li>Same PG major version required</li>
          <li>Read-only standby</li>
          <li>Simpler setup</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-card">
        <h3>Logical Replication</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Decoded row-level changes</li>
          <li>Per-table / selective</li>
          <li>Cross-version supported</li>
          <li>Writable subscriber</li>
          <li>More flexible, more complex</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 6: Point-in-Time Recovery -->
  <section class="flow-section">
    <h2>⏪ Point-in-Time Recovery (PITR)</h2>
    <p class="section-desc">Base backup + continuous WAL archiving = recover to any point in time.</p>

    <div class="flow-controls">
      <button id="pitrSetupBtn" class="action-btn primary-btn">▶ Setup Timeline</button>
      <button id="pitrResetBtn" class="action-btn reset-btn">🔄 Reset</button>
    </div>

    <div class="pitr-viz" id="pitrViz">
      <div class="pitr-empty">Click "Setup Timeline" to visualize a PITR scenario</div>
    </div>

    <div class="pitr-recovery" id="pitrRecovery" style="display: none;">
      <label>Recovery target time: <strong id="pitrTimeValue">—</strong></label>
      <input type="range" id="pitrSlider" min="0" max="100" value="50" step="1">
      <div class="pitr-recovery-info" id="pitrRecoveryInfo"></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Explanation: PITR -->
  <section class="explain-section">
    <div class="explain-card highlight-card">
      <h3>🔑 PITR in Practice</h3>
      <p>
        Run <code>pg_basebackup</code> to take a base backup. Configure <code>archive_command</code>
        to continuously copy WAL segments to a safe location. To recover: restore the base backup,
        point <code>restore_command</code> at your WAL archive, set <code>recovery_target_time</code>
        to the desired moment, and start PostgreSQL. It replays WAL up to that exact point—
        <strong>recovering every committed transaction up to the second</strong>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <footer class="viz-footer">
    <p>Based on <a href="https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/wal.html" target="_blank">PostgreSQL WAL Documentation</a> and <a href="https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/high-availability.html" target="_blank">High Availability Guide</a></p>
  </footer>

  <div class="share-buttons">
    <span>Share this visualization:</span>
    <a href="https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?text=Interactive%20visualization%20of%20PostgreSQL%20WAL%20and%20Replication&url=https://systeminternals.dev/postgresql/wal-replication/" target="_blank" class="share-btn">𝕏 Twitter</a>
    <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/sharing/share-offsite/?url=https://systeminternals.dev/postgresql/wal-replication/" target="_blank" class="share-btn">in LinkedIn</a>
    <a href="https://news.ycombinator.com/submitlink?u=https://systeminternals.dev/postgresql/wal-replication/&t=Interactive%20PostgreSQL%20WAL%20%26%20Replication%20Visualizer" target="_blank" class="share-btn">🟧 Hacker News</a>
  </div>
</div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .viz-container {
    max-width: 1100px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }

  .viz-header {
    text-align: center;
    margin-bottom: 40px;
  }

  .viz-header h1 {
    font-size: 2.5rem;
    margin-bottom: 10px;
    background: linear-gradient(90deg, #34d399, #60a5fa, #a78bfa);
    -webkit-background-clip: text;
    -webkit-text-fill-color: transparent;
    background-clip: text;
  }

  .subtitle {
    color: #888;
    font-size: 1.1rem;
  }

  h2 {
    font-size: 1.5rem;
    color: #fff;
    margin-bottom: 12px;
  }

  .section-desc {
    color: #888;
    margin-bottom: 24px;
    font-size: 1rem;
  }

  /* Overview */
  .overview-section {
    margin-bottom: 50px;
  }

  .overview-card {
    background: linear-gradient(135deg, rgba(52, 211, 153, 0.1), rgba(96, 165, 250, 0.05));
    border: 1px solid rgba(52, 211, 153, 0.3);
    border-radius: 16px;
    padding: 24px 28px;
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    line-height: 1.8;
    color: #ccc;
  }

  .overview-card strong { color: #fff; }
  .overview-card em { color: #34d399; font-style: normal; font-weight: 500; }

  /* Action Buttons */
  .action-btn {
    padding: 10px 20px;
    border: none;
    border-radius: 10px;
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    cursor: pointer;
    transition: all 0.2s;
  }

  .action-btn:disabled {
    opacity: 0.4;
    cursor: not-allowed;
  }

  .primary-btn {
    background: linear-gradient(135deg, #34d399, #059669);
    color: white;
  }

  .primary-btn:hover:not(:disabled) {
    transform: translateY(-2px);
    box-shadow: 0 5px 20px rgba(5, 150, 105, 0.4);
  }

  .step-btn {
    background: linear-gradient(135deg, #60a5fa, #3b82f6);
    color: white;
  }

  .delete-btn {
    background: linear-gradient(135deg, #f87171, #ef4444);
    color: white;
  }

  .gc-btn {
    background: linear-gradient(135deg, #f59e0b, #d97706);
    color: white;
  }

  .reset-btn {
    background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.1);
    color: #aaa;
  }

  .reset-btn:hover { background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.2); color: #fff; }

  /* Flow Section */
  .flow-section {
    margin-bottom: 50px;
  }

  .flow-controls {
    display: flex;
    gap: 12px;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    margin-bottom: 20px;
  }

  /* WAL Pipeline */
  .wal-pipeline {
    background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2);
    border-radius: 16px;
    padding: 24px;
    border: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.1);
    margin-bottom: 20px;
    overflow-x: auto;
  }

  .pipeline-stages {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0;
    min-width: 700px;
  }

  .pipeline-stage {
    flex: 1;
    text-align: center;
    padding: 16px 8px;
    border-radius: 12px;
    background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.03);
    border: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.08);
    transition: all 0.4s;
  }

  :global(.pipeline-stage.active) {
    background: rgba(52, 211, 153, 0.15);
    border-color: rgba(52, 211, 153, 0.5);
    box-shadow: 0 0 16px rgba(52, 211, 153, 0.3);
  }

  :global(.pipeline-stage.done) {
    background: rgba(52, 211, 153, 0.08);
    border-color: rgba(52, 211, 153, 0.2);
